e the career of the gendered body in the aesthetic tradition and the relationship among aesthetics, technics, politics, and figurative language. The author accounts for the hysteria that has characterized media representations of theory, explains why and how Romanticism has remained a locus of extravagant political hopes and anxieties, and, in a sequence of close readings, uncovers the “anaesthetic” condition of possibility of the politics of aesthetics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362003240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503620032423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503620032/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles